Abdul Qadeer Khan, known as the father of the Pakistani atomic bomb, supplied highly enriched uranium to Iran in 2001, fueling concerns about Iran's nuclear ambitions.
The Khan network's global black market in nuclear technology has implicated individuals in South Africa and Libya.
Despite allegations of collaboration with the US, Pakistani officials deny any involvement.
The CIA's report highlights the significance of Khan's contributions to Iran's nuclear program.
Questions remain about the extent of Pakistani military involvement and the recipients of Khan's nuclear expertise.
The Bush administration's reluctance to pursue Khan underscores the complexities of international nuclear proliferation.
